<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SLIDE 3: RUSHING IS IDENTITY -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="slide" id="s3" data-idx="2">
  <div style="max-width:820px;width:100%;">
    <div class="label" style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.4);">What Rushing Actually Is</div>
    <h2 style="color:var(--cream);">Rushing Is Not a<br><span style="color:var(--accent);">Speed Problem.</span></h2>

    <div class="rush-scene" id="rushScene">
      <div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.15em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.3);margin-bottom:14px;">What it sounds like inside your head when pressure hits</div>
      <div class="rush-transcript" id="rushTranscript">
        <span class="rush-word">Okay </span><span class="rush-word">I </span><span class="rush-word">need </span><span class="rush-word">to </span><span class="rush-word">get </span><span class="rush-word fast">this </span><span class="rush-word fast">out </span><span class="rush-word fast">before </span><span class="rush-word fast">they </span><span class="rush-word fast">interrupt— </span><span class="rush-word fast">the </span><span class="rush-word fast">main </span><span class="rush-word fast">point </span><span class="rush-word fast">is </span><span class="rush-word fast">basically </span><span class="rush-word trail">that </span><span class="rush-word trail">there </span><span class="rush-word trail">are </span><span class="rush-word trail">a </span><span class="rush-word trail">few </span><span class="rush-word trail">things </span><span class="rush-word trail">happening </span><span class="rush-word gone">and </span><span class="rush-word gone">kind </span><span class="rush-word gone">of </span><span class="rush-word gone">um </span><span class="rush-word gone">yeah </span><span class="rush-word gone">that's </span><span class="rush-word gone">basically </span><span class="rush-word gone">it.</span>
        <span class="rush-pulse"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="rush-caption">
        This is what rushing from the inside feels like. The words accelerate. Then they thin. Then the ending just — disappears. The room moves on. You know you had more to say. You just couldn't get there.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="rush-reasons" id="rushReasons">
      <div class="rush-reason">
        <div class="rush-dot"></div>
        <p><strong>Trying to prove you know enough</strong> before anyone has the chance to doubt you — so you front-load everything and trust nothing to land on its own.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rush-reason">
        <div class="rush-dot"></div>
        <p><strong>Getting through the discomfort faster</strong> — the speaking feels exposed, so you speed through it like sprinting past something that scares you.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rush-reason">
        <div class="rush-dot"></div>
        <p><strong>Afraid you will lose the room</strong> before you finish — so you compress everything into the first thirty seconds and abandon the part that would have actually landed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rush-reason">
        <div class="rush-dot"></div>
        <p><strong>Disconnected from what actually matters</strong> — when you don't know what your point is, you keep speaking until you accidentally find it. Or don't.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SLIDE 4: THE MOMENT IT BREAKS -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="slide" id="s4" data-idx="3">
  <div style="max-width:820px;width:100%;">
    <div class="label">The Anatomy of a Collapsed Message</div>
    <h2>Watch How It<br><span class="accent-text">Falls Apart.</span></h2>
    <p class="lead">It doesn't collapse all at once. There's a sequence — and once you can see it, you can catch it before it happens.</p>

    <div class="break-timeline" id="breakTimeline">
      <div class="break-moment">
        <div class="break-phase">The Setup — confidence intact</div>
        <h4>You know what you want to say.</h4>
        <p>Before you open your mouth, the thought is clear. You have the point. You know why it matters. The version of you that speaks in private is ready. <em>Then the room comes into focus.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-moment">
        <div class="break-phase">The Trigger — pressure lands</div>
        <h4>Someone important is watching. The stakes shift.</h4>
        <p>You feel it in your chest first. Then your jaw. Your pace quickens before you've said a word. You are no longer communicating — you are <em>performing your way through it.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-moment">
        <div class="break-phase">The Rush — structure dissolves</div>
        <h4>You speak faster. The shape disappears.</h4>
        <p>Words come out in the order they arrive, not the order they should land. You skip the core, over-explain the context, and <em>run out of energy before the ending.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-moment">
        <div class="break-phase">The Collapse — the ending vanishes</div>
        <h4>"And… yeah. That's basically it."</h4>
        <p>The most important part — the conclusion, the ask, the point you actually came to make — <em>never arrives.</em> You trail off. The room fills the silence for you. And you know exactly what just happened.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SLIDE 5: MEET THE CEO FRAMEWORK -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="slide" id="s5" data-idx="4">
  <div style="max-width:860px;width:100%;">
    <div class="label" style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.4);">The Framework</div>
    <div>
      <div class="ceo-wordmark">
        <span class="ceo-c">C</span><span class="ceo-e">E</span><span class="ceo-o">O</span>
      </div>
      <div class="ceo-sub">
        <span class="ceo-sub-item c">C — Core Message</span>
        <span class="ceo-sub-item e">E — Explain</span>
        <span class="ceo-sub-item o">O — Own the Ending</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="ceo-def" id="ceoDef">
      Three moves. Every speaking moment. Before you open your mouth, you know your core message, how you will support it, and <span>exactly how you will land it.</span> No more trailing off. No more hunting for the point mid-sentence. No more surviving the message — leading it.
    </div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.4);margin-top:20px;max-width:680px;">This framework works in meetings, pitches, negotiations, presentations, calls, voice notes, difficult conversations, and any moment where you need what you say to actually land. The next three slides go deep on each step.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SLIDE 6: C — CORE MESSAGE -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="slide" id="s6" data-idx="5">
  <div style="max-width:820px;width:100%;">
    <div class="ceo-step-hero">
      <div class="ceo-letter-big c">C</div>
      <div class="ceo-step-title">
        <div class="label" style="color:var(--ceo-c);">Step 1 — Core Message</div>
        <h2 style="color:var(--ink);">What is the one thing<br>you actually want to say?</h2>
        <p>Not five things. Not the whole backstory. Not every nuance you could possibly add. One message — the anchor everything else hangs off.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ceo-contrast">
      <div class="ceo-no">
        <div class="ceo-no-tag">Without it</div>
        <p>"So there are a few things going on and I wanted to kind of walk you through them because it's a bit complex and there's some context you need to understand first before we get to the main thing I wanted to talk about…"</p>
        <p style="margin-top:10px;font-size:12px;color:#b0a8a0;font-style:normal;">The listener is already lost. And you haven't said anything yet.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="ceo-yes">
        <div class="ceo-yes-tag">With it</div>
        <p>"The real issue is focus, not effort."</p>
        <p style="margin-top:10px;font-size:13px;color:var(--muted);font-style:normal;">Eight words. The room knows exactly where you are. Everything that follows lands against a clear anchor.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ceo-tip">
      <strong style="color:var(--ceo-c);">Before you speak, answer this:</strong> If I could only say one sentence in this entire conversation — what would it be? That sentence is your Core Message. Lead with it. Don't build to it.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SLIDE 7: E — EXPLAIN -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="slide" id="s7" data-idx="6">
  <div style="max-width:820px;width:100%;">
    <div class="ceo-step-hero">
      <div class="ceo-letter-big e">E</div>
      <div class="ceo-step-title">
        <div class="label" style="color:var(--ceo-e);">Step 2 — Explain</div>
        <h2 style="color:var(--ink);">Support it with<br>one or two things. Not seven.</h2>
        <p>One example. Two reasons. One way. Enough to make the core message land — not enough to bury it under its own evidence.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explain-phrases" id="explainPhrases">
      <div class="ep-row">
        <div class="ep-phrase">"I say that because…"</div>
        <div class="ep-why">Signals you are about to support the point — not wander away from it.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ep-row">
        <div class="ep-phrase">"One example is…"</div>
        <div class="ep-why">Commits to one. Resists the urge to add four more. The specificity does the work.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ep-row">
        <div class="ep-phrase">"What I mean is…"</div>
        <div class="ep-why">Reframes without backtracking. Useful when the core message needs one layer of unpacking.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ep-row">
        <div class="ep-phrase">"I say that for two reasons…"</div>
        <div class="ep-why">Tells the listener exactly how long this will take. Creates structure they can follow without effort.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ep-row">
        <div class="ep-phrase">"The clearest way I can put it is…"</div>
        <div class="ep-why">Commits to clarity before you deliver. Disciplines you to find the simplest version, not the most complete one.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explain-rule" id="explainRule">
      <p>The explain section is where most people lose control. The core message fires — and then the brain dumps everything it knows to prove the point was valid. <strong>Pick one thing. Say it clearly. Stop.</strong> The ending is next.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SLIDE 8: O — OWN THE ENDING -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="slide" id="s8" data-idx="7">
  <div style="max-width:820px;width:100%;">
    <div class="ceo-step-hero">
      <div class="ceo-letter-big o">O</div>
      <div class="ceo-step-title">
        <div class="label" style="color:var(--ceo-o);">Step 3 — Own the Ending</div>
        <h2 style="color:var(--ink);">Do not trail off.<br>Land the plane.</h2>
        <p>The ending is where authority lives or dies. Most people abandon it right before the finish line. You will not.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ending-types" id="endingTypes">
      <div class="ending-type">
        <div class="et-num">01</div>
        <h4>Return to the core message</h4>
        <p>Echo your opening point to close the loop. The listener hears the same anchor twice — once as a headline, once as a conclusion.</p>
        <div class="eg">"So that's why I keep coming back to the same thing — it's a focus issue, not an effort issue."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ending-type">
        <div class="et-num">02</div>
        <h4>State the conclusion clearly</h4>
        <p>Tell them what this means. Not what it is — what it means for them, for the decision, for what comes next.</p>
        <div class="eg">"So for me, the answer starts with picking one clear priority and removing everything else until that's done."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ending-type">
        <div class="et-num">03</div>
        <h4>Ask a direct question</h4>
        <p>Hand the conversation back with a specific ask. Not "does that make sense?" — a real question that moves something forward.</p>
        <div class="eg">"What would need to be true for that to work in your context?"</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="abandon-box">
      <strong>The trail-off is not modesty.</strong> It is the body pulling you back from the edge of being heard. Every time you own your ending — fully, deliberately, without shrinking — you teach your nervous system that it survived. That is how the pattern changes.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SLIDE 9: SIDE-BY-SIDE — WEAK vs CEO -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="slide" id="s9" data-idx="8">
  <div style="max-width:920px;width:100%;">
    <div class="label" style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.4);">Hear the Difference</div>
    <h2 style="color:var(--cream);">Same Topic.<br><span style="color:var(--accent2);">Completely Different Landing.</span></h2>
    <p style="font-size:16px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.5);max-width:700px;margin-bottom:0;">Read both versions out loud. Notice exactly where the weak version loses you — and what the CEO version does differently at every turn.</p>

    <div class="transcript-compare" id="transcriptCompare">
      <div class="tc-side weak">
        <div class="tc-tag">✗ No structure</div>
        <div class="tc-text">
          <span class="hl-bad">"I think the issue is kind of that,</span> I don't know, <span class="hl-bad">maybe</span> people are trying a lot of things and there's just a lot happening… and <span class="hl-bad">I guess</span> that can make them feel overwhelmed <span class="hl-bad">and yeah,</span> it's like they don't know where to focus… <span class="hl-bad">so that's basically it, I think."</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tc-obs">
          The point never lands. "Kind of." "Maybe." "I guess." "Basically." Each word is the speaker pulling back from their own message. The listener doesn't know what to do with this.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="tc-side strong">
        <div class="tc-tag">✓ CEO structure</div>
        <div class="tc-text">
          <span class="hl-c">"The real issue is lack of focus — not lack of effort."</span><span class="tc-label c">C</span><br><br>
          <span class="hl-e">"People try too many things at once, and because of that, they never build enough momentum in any one direction."</span><span class="tc-label e">E</span><br><br>
          <span class="hl-o">"So the solution, for me, starts with choosing one clear priority and protecting it."</span><span class="tc-label o">O</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tc-obs">
          Three sentences. One idea per sentence. The room knows exactly what was said, why it matters, and where things stand. Nothing is left hanging.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SLIDE 10: BUILD YOUR OWN — INTERACTIVE -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="slide" id="s10" data-idx="9">
  <div style="max-width:760px;width:100%;">
    <div class="label">Practice — Build It Right Now</div>
    <h2>Use the Framework<br><span class="accent-text">On Something Real.</span></h2>
    <p class="lead">Think of a message you need to deliver in the next 24 hours — a meeting, a call, a difficult conversation. Build it here before you walk in.</p>

    <div class="ceo-builder" id="ceoBuilder">
      <div class="cb-row c">
        <div class="cb-label"><div class="cb-letter c">C</div><span style="color:var(--ceo-c);">Core Message — your one sentence</span></div>
        <textarea class="cb-input" id="cInput" rows="2" placeholder="The one thing I need them to hear is…" oninput="updatePreview()"></textarea>
        <div class="cb-prompt">If you could only say one sentence — what is it? Lead with it, don't build to it.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cb-row e">
        <div class="cb-label"><div class="cb-letter e">E</div><span style="color:var(--ceo-e);">Explain — one reason, example, or way</span></div>
        <textarea class="cb-input" id="eInput" rows="2" placeholder="I say that because… / One example is… / What I mean is…" oninput="updatePreview()"></textarea>
        <div class="cb-prompt">One thing that makes the core message land. Resist adding a second. If you need a second, it goes here — and nowhere else.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cb-row o">
        <div class="cb-label"><div class="cb-letter o">O</div><span style="color:var(--ceo-o);">Own the Ending — decide it before you speak</span></div>
        <textarea class="cb-input" id="oInput" rows="2" placeholder="So for me… / Which means… / My question for you is…" oninput="updatePreview()"></textarea>
        <div class="cb-prompt">Return to the point, state the conclusion, or ask the direct question. Do not trail off. Decide the landing before you walk in.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="cb-preview" id="cbPreview">
        <div class="cb-preview-label">Your CEO message — read it out loud before the conversation</div>
        <div class="cb-preview-text" id="previewText"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SLIDE 11: CEO DAILY PRACTICE TRACKER -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SLIDE 12: COMMUNITY POSTS -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="slide" id="s12" data-idx="10">
  <div style="max-width:800px;width:100%;">
    <div class="label" style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.4);">Your Community Posts</div>
    <h2 style="color:var(--cream);">Two Things to<br><span style="color:var(--accent2);">Post Today.</span></h2>

    <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:20px;margin-top:28px;">
      <div class="log-card">
        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:10px;margin-bottom:14px;">
          <div style="background:var(--accent);color:white;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;padding:4px 12px;">Update · Comment 5/30</div>
        </div>
        <div class="log-header">Day 5/30 of "The Unmuted Voice Challenge"</div>
